"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_0_so_abood=self.webpackChunk_0_so_abood||[]).push([["379"],{4369(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"/2026/05/04/diy-react-to-langgraph","metadata":{"permalink":"/2026/05/04/diy-react-to-langgraph","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-04-diy-react-to-langgraph.md","title":"Why I Ditched My DIY ReAct Loop for LangGraph (And What I Lost in the Trade)","description":"Introduction","date":"2026-05-04T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"LangGraph","permalink":"/tags/langgraph","description":"LangGraph orchestration"},{"inline":false,"label":"Multi-Agent","permalink":"/tags/multi-agent","description":"Multi-agent AI systems"},{"inline":false,"label":"TypeScript","permalink":"/tags/typescript","description":"TypeScript development"},{"inline":true,"label":"react-loop","permalink":"/tags/react-loop"},{"inline":true,"label":"orchestration","permalink":"/tags/orchestration"},{"inline":false,"label":"AI","permalink":"/tags/ai","description":"Artificial intelligence and LLMs"}],"readingTime":8.01,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"0soAbood","socials":{"github":"https://github.com/Lorchissimo"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/Lorchissimo.png","key":"abood","page":null},{"name":"Claire","socials":{"github":"https://github.com/claire-username"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/0soabood.png","key":"claire","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Why I Ditched My DIY ReAct Loop for LangGraph (And What I Lost in the Trade)","date":"2026-05-04T00:00:00.000Z","tags":["langgraph","multi-agent","typescript","react-loop","orchestration","AI"],"authors":["abood","claire"],"category":"ai-engineering"},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Building a Local-First AI Shell from Scratch: Architecture Lessons from Aura","permalink":"/2026/05/03/building-aura-local-first-ai-shell"}},"content":"## Introduction\\n\\nAt some point when building a multi-agent system, you hit a wall. Your hand-rolled orchestration loop works fine in the demo. Then you add streaming. Then session resumption. Then multi-agent handoffs. Then a circuit breaker for runaway LLM loops.\\n\\nEach feature requires rewriting the same state management logic at a slightly lower level. By the time I had all of these in Aura \u2014 my local-first AI shell \u2014 the `ReactiveOrchestrator` class was a 300-line tangle of mutable state, `MAX_LOOPS` counters, and carefully ordered `if` statements.\\n\\nI rewrote it using [LangGraph](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraphjs/). This post is an honest accounting of what I gained, what the migration actually looked like, and one thing I genuinely lost.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What the DIY Loop Looked Like\\n\\nAura\'s original orchestration model was a **reactive blackboard**: every user message, agent output, and tool result gets appended to an immutable event log stored in SQLite. Agents read the full log and \\"bid\\" for control by returning a confidence score. The highest bidder executes.\\n{/* truncate */}\\nThe `ReactiveOrchestrator` class ran this in a `while` loop:\\n\\n```typescript\\n// Simplified from the original ReactiveOrchestrator.ts\\nconst MAX_LOOPS = 6;\\n\\nwhile (loopCount < MAX_LOOPS) {\\n  const bids = this.agents.map(a => a.evaluate(events));\\n  const winner = pickWinner(bids);\\n\\n  if (!winner || winner.confidence === 0) break;\\n\\n  const result = await winner.execute(events, bid);\\n  events.push(result); // append to blackboard\\n\\n  if (result.event_type === \'synthesis_complete\') break;\\n  if (result.event_type === \'escalation_required\') break;\\n\\n  loopCount++;\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis worked. Until I needed three things simultaneously:\\n\\n1. **SQLite-backed checkpointing** so sessions survive app restarts\\n2. **Streaming** \u2014 sending token-by-token output to the UI as it generates\\n3. **Multi-agent handoffs** where research output feeds code output feeds synthesis\\n\\nAll three require you to reason carefully about *when* state is written, *what* is persisted, and *how* partial results flow between agents. In a `while` loop, those concerns have no natural home. You end up patching in ad-hoc flags and writing increasingly defensive `if` chains.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Why LangGraph\\n\\nLangGraph models your orchestration as a **directed graph**: nodes are async functions (agents, tools, compaction passes), edges are routing decisions. State is a typed schema with declared reducers for each field.\\n\\nThe critical insight is that **state persistence and streaming become infrastructure concerns, not application concerns**. You plug in a `checkpointer` (SQLite, in our case) and LangGraph handles serialization, resume logic, and partial-state hydration automatically.\\n\\nHere\'s what Aura\'s graph definition looks like now:\\n\\n```typescript\\nexport const workflow = new StateGraph(AuraStateSchema)\\n  .addNode(\'orchestrator\', orchestratorNode)\\n  .addNode(\'research_agent\', specialistNode)\\n  .addNode(\'code_agent\', specialistNode)\\n  .addNode(\'synthesis_agent\', synthesisNode)\\n  .addNode(\'compaction\', compactionNode)\\n  .addEdge(START, \'orchestrator\');\\n\\nworkflow.addConditionalEdges(\'orchestrator\', (state) => {\\n  // Circuit breaker: 3 consecutive errors \u2192 force synthesis fallback\\n  if (state.errorCount >= 3) return \'synthesis_agent\';\\n  return state.activeAgent === \'end\' ? END : state.activeAgent;\\n});\\n\\nworkflow.addEdge(\'research_agent\', \'orchestrator\');\\nworkflow.addEdge(\'code_agent\', \'orchestrator\');\\nworkflow.addEdge(\'synthesis_agent\', \'compaction\');\\nworkflow.addEdge(\'compaction\', END);\\n\\nexport const compiledGraph = workflow.compile({\\n  checkpointer: new SqliteSaver(db), // same db instance as the rest of the app\\n});\\n```\\n\\nEvery loop iteration is now a graph traversal. The circuit breaker is a conditional edge. Session resumption is one line. The loop logic is in the graph structure, not in imperative code.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## The State Schema: Memory Separation by Design\\n\\nThe most consequential design decision in the migration was **how to separate memory**. The old blackboard was a single flat array. The new schema has explicit zones with different persistence semantics:\\n\\n```typescript\\nexport const AuraStateSchema = Annotation.Root({\\n  // PERSISTENT: user queries + final synthesized answers only\\n  // Survives session restarts. Reducer concatenates across turns.\\n  chatHistory: Annotation<BaseMessage[]>({\\n    reducer: (state, update) => state.concat(update),\\n    default: () => [],\\n  }),\\n\\n  // EPHEMERAL: agent scratchpad \u2014 reasoning traces, tool outputs, ReAct steps\\n  // Explicitly wiped by the compaction node after each turn.\\n  taskWorkspace: Annotation<BaseMessage[]>({\\n    reducer: (state, update) => update, // overwrite, not concat\\n    default: () => [],\\n  }),\\n\\n  // TELEMETRY: consecutive error count for the circuit breaker\\n  errorCount: Annotation<number>({\\n    reducer: (state, update) => state + update,\\n    default: () => 0,\\n  }),\\n});\\n```\\n\\nThe `taskWorkspace` overwrite reducer is the key move. Intermediate reasoning \u2014 tool call results, ReAct `[think]` / `[act]` / `[observe]` traces, pseudo-vector context injections \u2014 accumulates during a turn and then gets wiped by the compaction node. Only the clean final answer goes into `chatHistory`.\\n\\nThis solves **context rot**: the phenomenon where, over many turns, the LLM context window fills up with stale scratchpad content from previous sessions, degrading response quality and increasing token costs.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## The Compaction Node\\n\\nThe compaction node is a pattern I hadn\'t seen written about much but turned out to be essential. It runs after synthesis \u2014 not before \u2014 and does two things:\\n\\n1. **Extracts durable facts** from the ephemeral workspace using a cheap, fast model call\\n2. **Wipes `taskWorkspace` clean** for the next turn\\n\\n```typescript\\nasync function compactionNode(state: typeof AuraStateSchema.State) {\\n  const workspaceText = state.taskWorkspace.map(m => m.content).join(\'\\\\n\');\\n\\n  if (workspaceText.length > 100) {\\n    const prompt = `Review the following agent scratchpad and extract any newly discovered,\\npermanent facts about the user, their system, or project conventions.\\nIf nothing notable, reply exactly with \\"NONE\\".\\n\\nScratchpad:\\n${workspaceText.substring(0, 8000)}`;\\n\\n    const result = await registry.call(resolveModel(\'compaction\'), prompt, { temperature: 0.1 });\\n\\n    if (result.text && !result.text.includes(\'NONE\')) {\\n      // Persist to the USER.md memory file\\n      await toolRegistry.execute({\\n        name: \'write_memory\',\\n        arguments: { file: \'USER\', content: `Session facts:\\\\n${result.text.trim()}` }\\n      });\\n    }\\n  }\\n\\n  // Wipe the scratchpad\\n  return { taskWorkspace: [] };\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe compaction model call uses the cheapest available model (`resolveModel(\'compaction\')` maps to Gemini Flash or a Groq fast model). It runs after every turn but only writes to long-term memory when it finds something worth keeping. This gives Aura genuine cross-session memory without accumulating garbage.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Preserving the Blackboard Heuristics\\n\\nHere\'s the part that took the most work. The old `ReactiveOrchestrator` had battle-tested bid evaluation logic: keyword boosts for research and code queries, a synthesis guard that prevented the synthesis agent from \\"cutting in\\" before a specialist had run, and a circuit breaker.\\n\\nLangGraph didn\'t replace any of that \u2014 it just needed to host it. The `orchestratorNode` does the same bid evaluation as before, ported verbatim. The key addition is the **synthesis guard**:\\n\\n```typescript\\n// In orchestratorNode \u2014 runs on every loop iteration\\nconst synthIdx = bids.findIndex(b => b.agentName === \'synthesis_agent\');\\nif (synthIdx !== -1) {\\n  const specialistOutputExists = currentTurnEvents.some(\\n    e => (e.event_type === \'agent_output\' || e.event_type === \'code_written\')\\n      && e.author !== \'synthesis_agent\'\\n  );\\n  const specialistBiddingNow = bids.some(\\n    b => b.agentName !== \'synthesis_agent\' && b.confidence >= 0.30\\n  );\\n\\n  // Synthesis can only win if: a specialist already ran AND no specialist is competing\\n  const allowMode1 = synthBid.confidence >= 0.85 && specialistOutputExists && !specialistBiddingNow;\\n  // OR: it\'s a genuine greeting (hello, who are you, etc.)\\n  const allowMode2 = synthBid.confidence < 0.85 && isSynthesisGreeting(lastUserMsg);\\n\\n  if (!allowMode1 && !allowMode2) {\\n    bids[synthIdx] = { ...synthBid, confidence: 0 }; // suppress synthesis\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nWithout the synthesis guard, the synthesis agent \u2014 which has broad keyword coverage \u2014 would constantly outbid specialists and produce shallow responses that skipped the actual research or code generation step. The guard enforces turn ordering: specialists run first, synthesis runs last.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## The Bridge: `stateToEvents`\\n\\nThe migration wasn\'t a full rewrite of the agents themselves. Each agent still implements the same `ReactiveAgent` interface \u2014 `evaluate(events)` and `execute(events, bid)` \u2014 using the legacy `BlackboardEvent[]` format.\\n\\nTo keep agents working unchanged, I wrote a bridge function that converts LangGraph\'s `BaseMessage[]` state back into the legacy event format:\\n\\n```typescript\\nfunction stateToEvents(chatHistory: BaseMessage[], workspace: BaseMessage[]): BlackboardEvent[] {\\n  const events: BlackboardEvent[] = [];\\n\\n  for (const msg of [...chatHistory, ...workspace]) {\\n    if (msg._getType() === \'human\') {\\n      events.push({ event_type: \'user_message\', author: \'user\', content: msg.content, ... });\\n    } else if (msg._getType() === \'ai\') {\\n      let author = \'synthesis_agent\';\\n      // Map agent prefixes back to the correct author\\n      if (content.startsWith(\'[code_agent]\'))     { author = \'code_agent\'; }\\n      if (content.startsWith(\'[research_agent]\')) { author = \'research_agent\'; }\\n      // ...\\n      events.push({ event_type: \'agent_output\', author, content, ... });\\n    }\\n  }\\n  return events;\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis is a deliberate seam. Agent logic and orchestration logic are now cleanly separated. If I want to rewrite an agent to use native LangGraph state directly, I can do that incrementally without touching the graph structure.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What I Lost\\n\\nOne thing the DIY loop did naturally: **fine-grained control over when the loop terminates**.\\n\\nIn the old orchestrator, an agent could signal `synthesis_complete` and the loop would immediately stop \u2014 no further bids, no additional nodes. In the LangGraph version, the graph structure determines termination. The synthesis node always routes to compaction, and compaction always routes to END. That\'s the right architecture, but it means one extra LLM call (compaction) happens on every single turn, even trivial ones.\\n\\nFor a greeter response \u2014 \\"Hello! I\'m Aura\\" \u2014 the compaction node still spins up, reads the workspace (empty), finds nothing to extract, and exits. It\'s a fast no-op, but it\'s there.\\n\\nThe fix would be a conditional edge from `synthesis_agent` that skips compaction when the workspace is empty. I haven\'t added it yet because the overhead is negligible at current usage. But it\'s a real cost that didn\'t exist in the DIY loop.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Key Takeaways\\n\\n**Use LangGraph when you need:**\\n- Session resumption across restarts (SQLite checkpointer, one line)\\n- Streaming to a UI without managing partial state manually\\n- Multi-agent handoffs with clear state separation\\n- A circuit breaker that\'s structural, not imperative\\n\\n**Keep your own abstractions when:**\\n- Your agents have well-tested evaluation heuristics \u2014 port them, don\'t replace them\\n- You want incremental migration \u2014 the bridge pattern (`stateToEvents`) lets agents run unchanged\\n\\n**The compaction node is underrated.** Persistent memory + workspace wipe after every turn is the practical solution to context rot in long-running agents. Use a cheap model. Run it on every turn. Only write when there\'s something worth keeping.\\n\\n**The synthesis guard is not optional.** Any multi-agent system where one agent synthesizes the output of others needs an explicit rule preventing the synthesis agent from winning before the specialists have run. Without it, you get fast but shallow responses every time.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Conclusion\\n\\nThe migration from `ReactiveOrchestrator` to LangGraph was about two weeks of evenings. The agents didn\'t change. The blackboard heuristics didn\'t change. What changed was that session persistence, streaming, and loop control stopped being things I had to maintain and became things the framework handles.\\n\\nIf you\'re at the point where your orchestration loop has its own bugs, that\'s the signal. The DIY loop is a prototype. LangGraph is infrastructure.\\n\\n---\\n\\n*Built with: LangGraph \xb7 TypeScript \xb7 SQLite (`SqliteSaver`) \xb7 Electron \xb7 Vitest*"},{"id":"/2026/05/03/building-aura-local-first-ai-shell","metadata":{"permalink":"/2026/05/03/building-aura-local-first-ai-shell","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-03-building-aura-local-first-ai-shell.mdx","title":"Building a Local-First AI Shell from Scratch: Architecture Lessons from Aura","description":"Introduction","date":"2026-05-03T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"Electron","permalink":"/tags/electron","description":"Electron desktop app development"},{"inline":false,"label":"TypeScript","permalink":"/tags/typescript","description":"TypeScript development"},{"inline":false,"label":"Multi-Agent","permalink":"/tags/multi-agent","description":"Multi-agent AI systems"},{"inline":false,"label":"LangGraph","permalink":"/tags/langgraph","description":"LangGraph orchestration"},{"inline":false,"label":"React","permalink":"/tags/react","description":"React development"},{"inline":false,"label":"Local-First","permalink":"/tags/local-first","description":"Local-first software and offline-capable apps"},{"inline":false,"label":"AI","permalink":"/tags/ai","description":"Artificial intelligence and LLMs"}],"readingTime":6.53,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"0soAbood","socials":{"github":"https://github.com/Lorchissimo"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/Lorchissimo.png","key":"abood","page":null},{"name":"Claire","socials":{"github":"https://github.com/claire-username"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/0soabood.png","key":"claire","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Building a Local-First AI Shell from Scratch: Architecture Lessons from Aura","date":"2026-05-03T00:00:00.000Z","tags":["electron","typescript","multi-agent","langgraph","react","local-first","AI"],"authors":["abood","claire"],"category":"architecture"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Why I Ditched My DIY ReAct Loop for LangGraph (And What I Lost in the Trade)","permalink":"/2026/05/04/diy-react-to-langgraph"},"nextItem":{"title":"Setting Up This Blog with Docusaurus and GitHub Pages","permalink":"/2026/05/03/setting-up-this-blog"}},"content":"## Introduction\\r\\n\\r\\nMost AI tooling assumes you\'re comfortable with your data living in the cloud. Most productivity apps are built for neurotypical, always-online knowledge workers. I built **Aura** because I\'m neither of those things, and I was tired of tools that weren\'t built for me.\\r\\n\\r\\nAura is a local-first, multi-agent AI shell \u2014 an Electron + React desktop app that runs multiple specialized LLM agents on your machine, persists state in SQLite, and routes work through a ReAct orchestration loop built on LangGraph. Seven LLM providers. Neubrutalist editorial UI. Zero cloud dependency for core functionality.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis post walks through the architectural decisions I made, what broke, and what I\'d do differently.\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n## Background: The Problem with \\"Smart\\" AI Apps\\r\\n\\r\\nWhen you open most AI chat apps, you get a single conversation box. You talk to one model. It doesn\'t remember your projects. It doesn\'t know what you were doing yesterday. And every session starts completely cold.\\r\\n\\r\\nFor developers \u2014 especially those of us with ADHD \u2014 this is a brutal UX pattern. Context-switching already fragments executive function. An AI tool that *also* makes you re-explain your entire codebase every session is actively hostile.\\r\\n\\r\\nI wanted something different: an agent that holds your project state, knows which provider is cheapest for which task, persists everything locally, and has a UI designed around cognitive load reduction, not feature count.\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n## The Solution: A Multi-Agent Reactive Shell\\r\\n\\r\\nAura\'s architecture revolves around three core concepts:\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n### 1. The Blackboard Model\\r\\n\\r\\nInstead of a simple request/response cycle, Aura uses a **blackboard event system**. Every user message, agent output, tool result, and error is appended to an immutable event log stored in SQLite (`blackboard_events` table). Agents read the full log and *bid* for control.\\r\\n\\r\\n```typescript\\r\\nexport interface ReactiveAgent {\\r\\n  readonly name: AgentName;\\r\\n\\r\\n  // Synchronous \u2014 reads events, returns a confidence bid.\\r\\n  // Never calls an LLM at this stage.\\r\\n  evaluate(events: BlackboardEvent[]): AgentBid;\\r\\n\\r\\n  // Async \u2014 actually executes and returns output.\\r\\n  // The orchestrator writes results back to the blackboard.\\r\\n  execute(events: BlackboardEvent[], bid: AgentBid): Promise<AgentOutput>;\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nThis separation is intentional. The `evaluate` phase is pure \u2014 no LLM calls, no side effects. It\'s just keyword heuristics and event-count checks. Only the winning agent\'s `execute` runs asynchronously. This keeps the bid loop fast and debuggable.\\r\\n\\r\\n### 2. The Agent Roster\\r\\n\\r\\nAura currently ships four agents:\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Supervisor** \u2014 Routes work, chooses the best specialist, maintains task structure. Critically: it never exposes its routing reasoning to the user.\\r\\n- **Research Agent** \u2014 Retrieves and summarizes facts from context and tools. Never invents certainty.\\r\\n- **Code Agent** \u2014 Explains, generates, and patches code. Prefers small, safe diffs.\\r\\n- **Synthesis Agent** \u2014 Produces the final user-facing answer. Strips out all internal orchestration artifacts before responding.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe Synthesis Agent was the last to be added and turned out to be the most important. Without it, users were seeing `[research_agent]` internal tags and raw ReAct trace fragments leaking into responses. The Synthesis Agent is a dedicated \\"cleanup pass\\" that takes the full event log and produces a clean, readable final answer.\\r\\n\\r\\n### 3. LangGraph for Orchestration\\r\\n\\r\\nI originally rolled my own ReAct loop. It worked fine until I needed checkpointing, streaming, and multi-agent handoffs simultaneously. Three features, three different re-inventions of state machine logic.\\r\\n\\r\\nSwitching to **LangGraph** solved this cleanly. The graph-based workflow lets me define nodes (agents/tools) and edges (routing conditions) declaratively:\\r\\n\\r\\n```typescript\\r\\n// src/lib/graph/workflow.ts\\r\\nconst workflow = new StateGraph(AuraStateAnnotation)\\r\\n  .addNode(\\"supervisor\\", supervisorNode)\\r\\n  .addNode(\\"research\\", researchNode)\\r\\n  .addNode(\\"code\\", codeNode)\\r\\n  .addNode(\\"synthesis\\", synthesisNode)\\r\\n  .addEdge(START, \\"supervisor\\")\\r\\n  .addConditionalEdges(\\"supervisor\\", routeFromSupervisor)\\r\\n  .addEdge(\\"research\\", \\"synthesis\\")\\r\\n  .addEdge(\\"code\\", \\"synthesis\\")\\r\\n  .addEdge(\\"synthesis\\", END);\\r\\n\\r\\nexport const compiledGraph = workflow.compile({\\r\\n  checkpointer: new SqliteSaver(db),\\r\\n});\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nSQLite-backed checkpointing means sessions are resumable across restarts. This was essential for the \\"never lose context\\" requirement.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## The UI: Neubrutalist + ADHD-Calibrated\\r\\n\\r\\nThe original Aura UI was Tailwind utility classes everywhere. It worked, but it felt like every other React app. After the neubrutalist redesign \u2014 **Fraunces** serif headings, **JetBrains Mono** for data, thick borders, high contrast \u2014 the app started feeling like *mine*.\\r\\n\\r\\nMore importantly, I added five UX features specifically designed around ADHD:\\r\\n\\r\\n```\\r\\nPhase 5: ADHD-Calibrated UX Wins\\r\\n  \u2705 Energy Toggle (Low/High) as data-energy on <html>\\r\\n  \u2705 Brain Dump Mode \u2014 vague paragraph \u2192 auto-decomposed checklist\\r\\n  \u2705 Stream ReAct trace as discrete think/act/observe rows\\r\\n  \u2705 Session resumption badges in NavigationHub\\r\\n  \u2705 Keyboard-first density mode (Tab, Esc, /, g r shortcuts)\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n**Brain Dump Mode** deserves its own post. The core insight: with ADHD, the hardest moment isn\'t doing a task \u2014 it\'s decomposing \\"I need to do the thing\\" into actual steps. Brain Dump Mode accepts a raw, vague paragraph (\\"need to fix the auth flow and also update the readme and check why tests are failing\\") and uses an agent pass to decompose it into a structured checklist. It externalizes the executive function step that ADHD makes hardest.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Energy Toggle** is simpler but surprisingly effective. Low-energy mode dims non-essential UI, increases font sizes, and reduces motion. High-energy mode enables the full interface. One keypress. No settings menu to navigate.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## The Multi-Provider Setup\\r\\n\\r\\nAura supports seven LLM providers: Anthropic, Google (Gemini), Groq, OpenRouter, Mistral, Cohere, DeepSeek. The `ProviderRegistry` manages them behind a unified `UnifiedCaller` interface:\\r\\n\\r\\n```typescript\\r\\n// You call one method. The registry handles provider selection.\\r\\nconst result = await registry.call({\\r\\n  messages,\\r\\n  model: \\"gemini-2.0-flash\\",   // or \\"claude-sonnet-4-6\\", \\"llama-3.3-70b\\", etc.\\r\\n  tools: [...],\\r\\n  stream: true,\\r\\n});\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nAPI keys are stored locally in a `.env.local` file. Docker secrets are supported for containerized deployments. Nothing hits the network except the provider API calls themselves.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## What Broke (And What I Learned)\\r\\n\\r\\n### `better-sqlite3` vs Electron vs Node.js v22\\r\\n\\r\\nThis one cost me an entire day. `better-sqlite3` is a native Node.js module \u2014 it compiles to a `.node` binary that\'s ABI-specific. Electron uses its *own* Node.js ABI. Tests running under system Node.js v22 can\'t load the same binary that Electron built.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe fix: run tests inside Docker (where Node version is pinned to match the build environment), and rebuild the module specifically for Electron with `electron-rebuild`.\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# In package.json scripts:\\r\\n\\"rebuild:sqlite\\": \\"electron-rebuild -f -w better-sqlite3\\"\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nLesson: **native modules in Electron are always a layered versioning problem**. Plan for it upfront. Pin your Node version in CI.\\r\\n\\r\\n### The Synthesis Guard\\r\\n\\r\\nEarly Aura builds had a subtle bug where the supervisor\'s internal routing reasoning (`routing_decision: research_agent, confidence: 0.87`) was leaking into user-facing responses. This happened because the final node was writing whatever was in `state.lastAgentOutput` directly to the UI.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe fix was adding an explicit synthesis guard in the orchestrator node \u2014 keyword checks that catch and strip internal tags before the response reaches the renderer:\\r\\n\\r\\n```typescript\\r\\n// In workflow.ts orchestratorNode\\r\\nconst INTERNAL_TAG_PATTERN = /\\\\[(supervisor|research_agent|code_agent)\\\\]/gi;\\r\\nconst cleanedOutput = rawOutput.replace(INTERNAL_TAG_PATTERN, \'\').trim();\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nPlus the dedicated Synthesis Agent, which now owns the final pass.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## Key Takeaways\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Separate bid from execute** \u2014 keep agent selection synchronous and pure, agent execution async. This makes the loop debuggable and fast.\\r\\n- **LangGraph > DIY ReAct** when you need checkpointing + streaming + multi-agent state. The abstraction cost is worth it.\\r\\n- **The Synthesis Agent is not optional** \u2014 without a dedicated cleanup pass, internal orchestration artifacts leak to users.\\r\\n- **Native modules in Electron require explicit rebuild steps** \u2014 don\'t fight it, automate it.\\r\\n- **ADHD-calibrated UX is universal UX** \u2014 Energy Toggle, Brain Dump, keyboard shortcuts make the app better for everyone, not just neurodivergent users.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## Conclusion\\r\\n\\r\\nAura is still in active development. The next milestones are the Veto Layer (tiered authorization so agents can\'t take destructive actions without confirmation), Firecrawl integration for live web access, and automating my Etsy product listing pipeline.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe architecture is solid. The UI feels right. And for the first time, I have an AI tool that doesn\'t make me feel like I\'m fighting it.\\r\\n\\r\\nIf you\'re building something similar \u2014 local-first, multi-agent, ADHD-aware \u2014 I\'d love to compare notes. Find me in the repo.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n*Built with: Electron \xb7 React \xb7 TypeScript \xb7 LangGraph \xb7 SQLite \xb7 Radix UI \xb7 Zustand \xb7 Vitest \xb7 Docker*"},{"id":"/2026/05/03/setting-up-this-blog","metadata":{"permalink":"/2026/05/03/setting-up-this-blog","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-03-setting-up-this-blog.mdx","title":"Setting Up This Blog with Docusaurus and GitHub Pages","description":"I wanted a place to write. Not a newsletter, not a Twitter thread \u2014 just a quiet corner of the internet where I can think out loud about things I\'m building and learning.","date":"2026-05-03T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"General","permalink":"/tags/general","description":"General posts"},{"inline":false,"label":"Web","permalink":"/tags/web","description":"Web development and frontend topics"},{"inline":false,"label":"Tutorial","permalink":"/tags/tutorial","description":"Step-by-step guides and walkthroughs"}],"readingTime":2.88,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"0soAbood","socials":{"github":"https://github.com/Lorchissimo"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/Lorchissimo.png","key":"abood","page":null},{"name":"Claire","socials":{"github":"https://github.com/claire-username"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/0soabood.png","key":"claire","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Setting Up This Blog with Docusaurus and GitHub Pages","date":"2026-05-03T00:00:00.000Z","authors":["abood","claire"],"tags":["general","web","tutorial"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Building a Local-First AI Shell from Scratch: Architecture Lessons from Aura","permalink":"/2026/05/03/building-aura-local-first-ai-shell"},"nextItem":{"title":"Hello, World","permalink":"/2026/05/02/hello-world"}},"content":"I wanted a place to write. Not a newsletter, not a Twitter thread \u2014 just a quiet corner of the internet where I can think out loud about things I\'m building and learning.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis post is about how I set up this blog: the stack I chose, the few gotchas I ran into, and why the whole thing took less than an afternoon.\\r\\n\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n## Why Docusaurus?\\r\\n\\r\\nThe requirements were simple: write in Markdown, deploy to GitHub Pages for free, and not spend two weekends configuring webpack. I looked at a few options \u2014 Jekyll, Hugo, Astro, 11ty \u2014 and landed on **Docusaurus** for a few reasons:\\r\\n\\r\\n1. It\'s maintained by Meta\'s open source team and has active development\\r\\n2. It supports **MDX** out of the box, so I can drop React components into posts if I ever want to\\r\\n3. Blog-only mode means I get a clean blog without the docs sidebar I don\'t need\\r\\n4. It handles RSS/Atom feeds, reading-time estimates, and author profiles without plugins\\r\\n\\r\\n## Scaffolding the Project\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nnpx create-docusaurus@latest my-blog classic\\r\\ncd my-blog\\r\\nnpm install\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nThe classic preset gives you docs + blog. Since I only want the blog, I needed to turn off the docs section and make the blog serve from the root path.\\r\\n\\r\\n## Blog-Only Mode\\r\\n\\r\\nIn `docusaurus.config.js`, inside the `presets` array, change the blog plugin config:\\r\\n\\r\\n```js\\r\\npresets: [\\r\\n  [\\r\\n    \'classic\',\\r\\n    {\\r\\n      docs: false,  // disable the docs plugin entirely\\r\\n      blog: {\\r\\n        routeBasePath: \'/\',  // serve blog from the site root\\r\\n        showReadingTime: true,\\r\\n        feedOptions: {\\r\\n          type: [\'rss\', \'atom\'],\\r\\n          xslt: true,\\r\\n        },\\r\\n        onInlineTags: \'warn\',\\r\\n        onInlineAuthors: \'warn\',\\r\\n        onUntruncatedBlogPosts: \'warn\',\\r\\n      },\\r\\n      theme: {\\r\\n        customCss: \'./src/css/custom.css\',\\r\\n      },\\r\\n    },\\r\\n  ],\\r\\n],\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nWith `docs: false` and `routeBasePath: \'/\'`, the homepage is now your blog listing. Clean.\\r\\n\\r\\n## GitHub Pages Configuration\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\nAlso worth adding `trailingSlash: false` explicitly \u2014 without it you\'ll see a warning about inconsistent trailing slash behavior during deployment, which can cause issues with some hosting setups:\\r\\n\\r\\n```js\\r\\ntrailingSlash: false,\\r\\n```\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n## Authors and Tags\\r\\n\\r\\nDocusaurus supports a structured authors file. Create `blog/authors.yml`:\\r\\n\\r\\n```yaml\\r\\nabood:\\r\\n  name: 0soAbood\\r\\n  image_url: https://github.com/YourUsername.png\\r\\n  socials:\\r\\n    github: YourUsername\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nAnd `blog/tags.yml` for consistent tag metadata:\\r\\n\\r\\n```yaml\\r\\ngeneral:\\r\\n  label: General\\r\\n  permalink: /general\\r\\n  description: General posts\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nThen in any post\'s frontmatter:\\r\\n\\r\\n```yaml\\r\\n---\\r\\ntitle: \\"My Post Title\\"\\r\\ndate: 2026-05-03\\r\\nauthors: abood\\r\\ntags: [general]\\r\\n---\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n## Dark Mode\\r\\n\\r\\nOne line in `themeConfig`:\\r\\n\\r\\n```js\\r\\nthemeConfig: {\\r\\n  colorMode: {\\r\\n    respectPrefersColorScheme: true,\\r\\n  },\\r\\n  // ...\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nThis makes the blog respect the user\'s OS-level dark/light preference automatically. No toggle required.\\r\\n\\r\\n## The Result\\r\\n\\r\\nThe whole setup \u2014 scaffolding, configuration, writing the first post, and getting it ready to deploy \u2014 took a few hours. The project structure is minimal:\\r\\n\\r\\n```\\r\\nmy-blog/\\r\\n\u251C\u2500\u2500 blog/\\r\\n\u2502   \u251C\u2500\u2500 authors.yml\\r\\n\u2502   \u251C\u2500\u2500 tags.yml\\r\\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 2026-05-03-first-post.mdx\\r\\n\u251C\u2500\u2500 src/\\r\\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 css/\\r\\n\u2502       \u2514\u2500\u2500 custom.css\\r\\n\u251C\u2500\u2500 static/\\r\\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 img/\\r\\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 docusaurus.config.js\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nNo database, no CMS, no server. Just Markdown files committed to a repo that deploys automatically via GitHub Actions.\\r\\n\\r\\n## Key Takeaways\\r\\n\\r\\n- Set `docs: false` and `routeBasePath: \'/\'` to get a blog-only Docusaurus site\\r\\n- Always update the `url`, `organizationName`, and `projectName` fields in the config before deploying\\r\\n- Add `trailingSlash: false` to avoid GitHub Pages redirect inconsistencies\\r\\n- `authors.yml` and `tags.yml` keep your post metadata consistent across posts\\r\\n- `respectPrefersColorScheme: true` gives you free dark mode with zero extra work\\r\\n\\r\\n## What\'s Next\\r\\n\\r\\nNow that the plumbing is in place, I can focus on writing. I have a few topics already queued up. We\'ll see what makes it out of my notes and onto the page.\\r\\n\\r\\nIf you\'re thinking about starting a blog with a similar setup, the Docusaurus [blog documentation](https://docusaurus.io/docs/blog) is genuinely good \u2014 worth a read before you start."},{"id":"/2026/05/02/hello-world","metadata":{"permalink":"/2026/05/02/hello-world","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-02-hello-world.mdx","title":"Hello, World","description":"First post. Not much to say yet \u2014 I\'m still figuring out what this place is going to be.","date":"2026-05-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"General","permalink":"/tags/general","description":"General posts"}],"readingTime":0.25,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"0soAbood","socials":{"github":"https://github.com/Lorchissimo"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/Lorchissimo.png","key":"abood","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Hello, World","date":"2026-05-02T00:00:00.000Z","authors":"abood","tags":["general"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Setting Up This Blog with Docusaurus and GitHub Pages","permalink":"/2026/05/03/setting-up-this-blog"}},"content":"First post. Not much to say yet \u2014 I\'m still figuring out what this place is going to be.\\n\\n\\n\\nThe plan is to write about things I find interesting as I come across them. No specific topic, no schedule, just stuff worth putting into words.\\n\\nIf you\'re reading this somehow: hi."}]}}')}}]);